    <h3 class="landmark heading" id="work">Chapter Text</h3>
    <p> </p><p>On the first night of their new adventure, before they meet the god, the eight of them build a fire in the woods. It burns hot and bright in the relentless fog. The stars are shrouded beyond reach; the air still, the trees calm. They are adrift in history.</p><p> </p><p>“Has anyone ever met giant llama people?” Wild asks, flames casting a bronze shadow across the burn scars on his face.</p><p> </p><p>Warriors straightens slightly, listening as everyone around the circle dissents with varying degrees of incredulity. The man with the blue cap and peach-pink bangs, fingers ringed with gold—the one who immediately called him a prick when Warriors introduced himself as a captain in the Queen’s Army—quirks a crooked eyebrow, as if to say, <em> giant llama people? Can you believe it? </em></p><p> </p><p>Warriors digs his fingernails into his scarred palm. He can’t. Maybe the War was supposed to teach him, and maybe he should be used to stumbling into myths and fairytales, into the past, but he has never been so violently lost before. The fairytales have always come to <em> him, </em>to where he had battalions and generals and marching orders. There have always been expectations.</p><p> </p><p>Now they have no map and no leader and no common Queen to unite them. The sailor is younger, barely more than a preteen, and the masked child is nowhere to be found. The loss is a dull, relentless ache.</p><p> </p><p>“Nobody?” Wild sighs, and flops off his log to land sprawled across the grass. Twilight pokes him with one booted foot and he sticks out his tongue in lazy retaliation.</p><p> </p><p>“Cub, why would we’ve seen giant—whatsit?”</p><p> </p><p>“Llama,” says Wind helpfully.</p><p> </p><p>“Llama people?” Twilight finishes. </p><p> </p><p>“I don’t know,” says Wild. The fire sputters. “There was a Zonai Kingdom, for a while, instead of Hyrule. I’m trying to figure out where I am on the timeline.”</p><p> </p><p>Silence sweeps over their group of eight like winter, swift and cold. The chatter dies down.</p><p> </p><p>“If you don’t know what a llama is, I could show you a picture?” Wild offers.</p><p> </p><p>Warriors pictures Impa, just behind Zelda’s thin shoulder, eyes like carnelians. <em> They say that time was broken, long ago, </em> she rasps in his brain, the echo of her inside him. <em> Something happened—our records are lacking, after hundreds of years. All we know is— </em></p><p> </p><p>“A fracture,” he says aloud.</p><p> </p><p>Everyone turns to him in unison. He shakes Impa away. </p><p> </p><p>“A Sheikah warrior of my time,” he explains, “believed that time used to move in three concurrent rivers. Three parallel timelines, if you will.”</p><p> </p><p>He meets blank stares head-on, lifting his chin and flattening his palms by his side. “Our best guess is that it involved divine intervention of some kind. In the War, we were allied with many powerful mages, including some that could manipulate the flow of time—but none who could break it or split it. A <em> mortal </em>who could do that would be… impossibly powerful.”</p><p> </p><p>“Three timelines…” Four breathes. His name has been easy for Warriors to remember—chiefly because it makes the least amount of sense. “Oh, the implications…”</p><p> </p><p>“I know I’m after you,” says the young brown-haired boy that has been hovering around the edges of the group since they met. Warriors follows his dark-eyed gaze across the clearing. </p><p> </p><p>It lands on the man with the blue cap, who lifts his head. </p><p> </p><p>“Me?” he asks. His voice sounds alien without the bitter edge colouring the words.</p><p> </p><p>“The Hero of Legend,” the boy breathes. He moves closer. Everyone in the camp settles. “You’re a story.”</p><p> </p><p>Legend barks a short laugh. “I suppose it would’ve been too much to hope that Ganon would stay dead.”</p><p> </p><p>The boy shakes his head. What was his name? Why can’t Warriors remember? “He did,” he insists. “For so long that we forgot to watch for him in the night.”</p><p> </p><p>Legend suddenly looks like a man drowning. The boy reaches out, fingers light, as if to touch a monument. </p><p> </p><p>Warriors watches them. The boy’s hand curls into Legend’s fingers and the blue-capped hero shudders soundlessly. What does it feel like to hold history in the palm of your hand? What does it feel like to hold the future? </p><p> </p><p>The silence stretches on, and neither of them let go.</p><p> </p><p>“You must live in an era after mine,” Twilight says to Wild. The moment shatters. The nameless boy retreats. “That slate is like no technology I’ve ever seen before.”</p><p> </p><p>“Who’s before me, then?”</p><p> </p><p>“I know who’s before me,” Wind offers. Warriors glances at him briefly. </p><p> </p><p>It was strange having to introduce himself to his own brother. He observes from a careful distance the baby fat in Wind’s cheeks, seeing the places where it will thin and where the bone structure of his jawline will emerge. </p><p> </p><p>“Who?” Sky asks.</p><p> </p><p>Wind leans forward, ushering them closer, as if he’s about to tell a secret. Warriors leans in despite himself. The kid had always been charismatic; a storyteller. The memories of his brother are plastered on top of this foreign young version despite all efforts to redirect his thinking. A living ghost, who gets pissed off more often than amused and whose blond hair is curlier than Warriors ever saw it.</p><p> </p><p>“The Hero of Time,” the sailor says. His voice comes like a breath of wind. They collectively shiver. The Hero of Time is a boogeyman; a wraith. Something that lurks around the edges of every story.</p><p> </p><p>Mist envelopes them. Warriors glances back at the pale trees, but they are alone.</p><p> </p><p>“I met his ghost, once,” Twilight says. “Or spirit? I couldn’t tell.”</p><p> </p><p>“Wait, the Hero of Time?” Legend asks. </p><p> </p><p>Wind nods, and wiggles his fingers mock-spookily. “They called me the Hero of Time Reborn, but that wasn’t true. I didn’t have the right spirit. He saved the world, then vanished, and the goddesses sent the flood…”</p><p> </p><p>“But he died,” Legend says.</p><p> </p><p>Everyone stills. </p><p> </p><p>“Three timelines,” Four remembers. “Have you heard of him, Sky?” </p><p> </p><p>The Skyloftian shakes his head. A huge piece of thin silky fabric is folded up and tucked like a cape on his back. Warriors caught glimpses of pale blue embroidery earlier when he bent down to retrieve a whittling knife from his pack—he carves a chunk of firewood idly as they talk. “All the records of the time before the Chaos Wars have been lost entirely,” he says. “But I suppose it’s feasible.”</p><p> </p><p>“Has anyone here heard of the Chaos Wars?” Four asks. “No?”</p><p> </p><p>“Maybe I’m at the end of the timeline, then,” Sky says. He peels another strip of wood from the block. What is he making? “The Chaos Wars were… you would have heard of them, if they’d happened in your past. They were…”</p><p> </p><p>“I’ve heard of a few wars,” Wild says. “But not that one.” </p><p> </p><p>Warriors tenses. “One of those might’ve been mine.”</p><p> </p><p>“Yeah,” Wild says. He blinks. It seems purposeful, like he might’ve forgotten earlier and was making up for it now. His irises are almost electric blue. The same colour as his slate, Warriors realises. It’s offputting. “I think it was.”</p><p> </p><p>“So that gives us our three rivers of time that converge,” Four tells them. He picks up a stick from their pile of firewood and digs it into the ground. Soft dark earth is overturned as he draws. “One river for the sailor, one for the veteran and the traveller and the rancher, and one for—? Me, maybe?”</p><p> </p><p>“Is the rancher after or before the traveller and veteran?” Sky asks thoughtfully.</p><p> </p><p>Four shrugs. Warriors bites the inside of his lip. The <em> traveller. </em>Hyrule. That was the boy’s name. Was he one of the heroes depicted in the Temple of Souls? Should Warriors be ashamed that he doesn’t know more of his own history? Cia’s obsession had been hard to face, even after she was defeated. He’d tried not to look any of the statues in the eyes.</p><p> </p><p>“I don’t know much of history,” Twilight says apologetically. “My village has been farming land for centuries.”</p><p> </p><p>“There are no farmlands anymore,” says Hyrule. “But I haven’t heard of you.” </p><p> </p><p>“Does that mean it goes rancher, veteran, traveller?” Four asks.</p><p> </p><p>“No,” says Legend. “The Hero of Time came directly before me. There’s a grave in Hyrule Field that’s only a couple of decades old.”</p><p> </p><p>“This doesn’t make sense,” Twilight says.</p><p> </p><p>“You must be from parallel worlds, then,” Four says. </p><p> </p><p>“He’s the third river,” Legend realises.</p><p> </p><p>“Yes. And then we have our captain,” Four says decisively. The tip of the stick hovers over the diagram, before he extends each of the lines. He jabs the stick down sharply to create a point at which they all meet. “You knew about all three of the branches,” he continues. “You must be the future of all of them. And after you, the cook.”</p><p> </p><p>Wind cranes his neck to look at the diagram. “What about you?” </p><p> </p><p>Four chews the inside of his mouth for a moment. “I… haven’t heard of anyone else,” he admits. “Maybe I’m here?” He points at the third timeline, after the mark representing Twilight. “Or I could be here.” </p><p> </p><p>The stick moves to the line between Warriors and Wild. “This has to be a long time,” he says, “because none of us have heard of the Zonai. And Wild’s technology is so complex.”</p><p> </p><p>Wind snorts. “It can’t be <em> that </em> advanced,” he says. “In my time, the old pirates say there’s a land to the west where the people ride around in machines on rails.”</p><p> </p><p>“What about after Wild and before Sky?” Twilight offers.</p><p> </p><p>“Yeah, that could make sense,” Wild agrees. “A lot of our oral history was destroyed when… well, we still have records, but it’s not uncommon to find small settlements that are mostly cut off from the wider world.”</p><p> </p><p>“Okay.” Four tosses the stick into the fire and leans over his drawing. “There. That’s all eight of us.”</p><p> </p><p>“And the Hero of Time,” Twilight points out. The fire crackles. “He’s at the top. The beginning of the world.”</p><p> </p><p>“He must have split the timelines,” Legend murmurs. Hyrule drifts closer, peering over his shoulder.</p><p> </p><p>“I thought you said a mortal couldn’t do that,” Sky says.</p><p> </p><p>Impa’s eyes, like carnelians. <em> They say that time was broken, long ago. </em></p><p> </p><p>“Maybe I was wrong,” Warriors says aloud. “Or… maybe I wasn’t.”</p><p> </p><p>Beside the fire, Wind shivers.</p><p> </p><p>He has to say something.</p><p> </p><p>“In the war,” Warriors starts, watching them turn towards him like the battlefield crows to carrion; like men to the blade that brings their deaths: “I met other heroes from other times. One of them was a child.”</p><p> </p><p>“You let a child fight in a <em> war?” </em>Legend snaps.</p><p> </p><p>Twilight’s brow creases.</p><p> </p><p>“I had no choice,” Warriors says, and begins to laugh. “He was more powerful than I was and didn’t take no for an answer. I sent him away, I gave him errands, I assigned soldiers to watch him. He slipped them all. On the battlefield…”</p><p> </p><p>He swallows.</p><p> </p><p>“He carried masks,” he continues, forcing the words out. “The masks… changed him. Allowed him to take the shape of other creatures.”</p><p> </p><p>Wild makes a curious noise.</p><p> </p><p>“One was more powerful than the rest. A hylian face—or, it <em> looked </em>hylian. When he wore it… he was taller than two men stacked. There were coloured tattoos on his face. His skin was… leeched of colour. Eyes went white.”</p><p> </p><p>Warriors hides his shaking hands in his scarf. He’d slipped on a corpse and fallen. A moblin had decided to take the opportunity to skewer him. It hadn’t been the first time he’d known with cold, detached clarity that he was about to die, but it had been one of the worst.</p><p> </p><p>Then the silver double helix had come down like a bolt of lightning on the moblin, splitting apart the bone of its skull easier than Warriors shelled peanuts. The giant had tilted his head and <em> looked </em>at him cowering in the mud. Eyes blank. Eerily silent. He hadn’t known it was the child, underneath, back then. He’d thought it was some sort of angel. The giant stood alone on the battlefield, like a pillar in the grey rain, while soldiers scrambled for their swords.</p><p> </p><p><em> Stand down, </em> Warriors had managed through a broken rib, before they carried him away. <em> He’s an ally. </em></p><p> </p><p>“The child was a hero in his own right.” He clears his throat. “But the mask… he didn’t like to talk about it. He wouldn’t tell me where it came from or how he got a hold on it.”</p><p> </p><p>“But you think you know?” Legend says, eyes glittering. He leans in closer, eyebrows furrowed.</p><p> </p><p>Warriors swallows. “I think I do,” he agrees. “The child mentioned a town of clocks, once, when he was half-asleep. And he used to flinch when Impa spoke of the splitting of the timeline—he was very sensitive to discussions of history. He told me the mask was modelled from the body of a great warrior.”</p><p> </p><p>“You think it was modelled off the Hero of Time,” Legend finished.</p><p> </p><p>“It could be,” Four mused. “Most gods have true forms. And shape like that has power.”</p><p> </p><p>“Do you think he’ll join us on this adventure?” Twilight wonders.</p><p> </p><p>“I don’t know,” Warriors says. He buries the child’s echo again in the hollow recesses of his memory. The laughter, the pranks, the late nights exchanging insults and trivia—they belong with the sailor’s older self, not here by the fireside surrounded by strangers. He flicks his gaze over Wind. “You would’ve liked Mask, by the way.”</p><p> </p><p>“Maybe he’ll join us,” says his brother who is no longer his brother.</p><p> </p><p>“Maybe,” lies Warriors. He aches to reach out and ruffle the kid’s hair. He never expected to see the sailor again after the War, but the pang in his heart is bittersweet. “It's an impossible conjecture. The Hero of Time could be anyone.”</p><p> </p><p>“More of a myth than a man,” Sky agrees. He yawns. The wood in his hands is taking on the shape of a bird. “If he ever existed at all.”</p><p> </p><p>“Someone must’ve died using his name,” Legend says, his face awash in shadow. “Or Ganon wouldn’t have tried to kill me when I was a kid.”</p><p><br />
<br />
</p><p> </p><hr /><p> </p><p><br />
<br />
</p><p>It is not a hero’s right to question the gods. </p><p> </p><p>Link—Time, now—emerges from the portal, and shakes off the eddies of thick, buzzing energy that cling to his armour. He can taste Hylia’s brand of divinity on the back of his tongue. It’s icy and sweet and familiar. He almost feels the phantom sensation of the ocarina in his palms. </p><p> </p><p>The strange men are waiting for him on the other side. If they can be called men<em> . </em></p><p> </p><p>It had been a shock, at first, to hear them introduce themselves. <em> I’m known as Warriors, </em> the creature holding out his hand in hylian greeting fashion had said. <em> This is Wind… </em>His skin was warm. It was strange. Time has never been allowed to touch a god before. What a sight they had made in the Lost Woods, all eight of them surrounded by great coils of magic, pulsing through them and around them. It had taken all he had not to clam up like a child when they said he was welcome in their group. </p><p> </p><p>A man walking among immortals. Malon is not going to <em> believe </em>this.</p><p> </p><p>The one he shook hands with is representative of warriors. Fitting, then, that he wears a similar-looking pauldron as the young captain from Time’s childhood, whose face and voice is now lost to his fading memory. The others range from gleeful to surly, but each of them have a facade of youth. The Wind has taken the shape of a <em> boy, </em>for Nayru’s sake: as playful and impulsive as the element he is made of. It is absurd to realise Time appears to be the eldest of them.</p><p> </p><p>Time squints into the afternoon sun and the battlements around. They’ve arrived in a courtyard, paved with diamonds. The shapes tease… He’s been to this place, long ago. It’s familiar.</p><p> </p><p>“Ooh, this is Warriors’ <em> least </em>favourite Hyrule,” the child-shaped god says cheerfully. </p><p> </p><p>“Is not,” Warriors grumbles. “That’d make me a traitor.”</p><p> </p><p>“You flinched when you recognised it,” another of the group points out. This god—<em>Legend, </em>a creature of storytelling—has little furrows in his forehead. It’s so realistic.</p><p> </p><p>“Yeah, because I don’t want whatever we’re fighting on this quest to be <em> here. </em>Where all these poor souls finally found peace.”</p><p> </p><p>“Mm,” says Sky. </p><p> </p><p>Hyrule sighs. “Okay, that’s fair.”</p><p> </p><p>Time suppresses a wide-eyed stare. He still can’t believe… He catches two of the others looking at him intently and tilts his head in their direction. They glance away.</p><p> </p><p>“Let’s head for the Castle’s inner circle,” Warriors decides. “We can get advice from the Queen’s court.”</p><p> </p><p>“You just miss your soldier friends, I bet,” the Wind teases.</p><p> </p><p>Warriors shoots him an awkward glance. Time imagines him watching over the armies during times of bloodshed. Does he often walk among them disguised as a common soldier? Do they know him for what he truly is?</p><p> </p><p>Did he ever meet Time’s older brothers? This is the land his eldest brother was born in—the same castle and battlegrounds and sun glinting off metal. And Time has travelled through an odd portal to get here, the same as last time. This place must be a long way away, he considers, not for the first time. He’d checked the maps when he got home from the war as a kid and couldn’t find the battleground he’d fought at on any single one. A long, <em> long </em>distance, if they must resort to some kind of teleportation magic to arrive despite Twilight owning a horse. </p><p> </p><p>But then he had never been able to find Termina on any map either. Nor been able to lead Epona there. </p><p> </p><p>And why does the magic so clearly come from Hylia? Could none of the gods use their own? He worries his lip and glances at Hyrule—at the personification of his <em> country. </em> There are glittery wings in the shadow he casts—faint, but distinct, if you know where to look. He smells like fairies. He smells like fairies even more than <em> Time </em>smells like fairies, despite the fact that the way Malon’s friends tell it, he’s more than half a fairy himself. Changeling, they call him. It pales next to Hyrule’s flower-sweet coils of magic. </p><p> </p><p>Is there a reason he’s not using his own power? They said that Hylia had sent them on a mission. Is that it? Is there something wrong with—?</p><p> </p><p>Warriors leads them up a long hallway. They pass a brazier set into the wall and a vague memory stirs within him. Being a child, and running—running to the hiding-place he’d found a week before. The young captain hot on his heels, brandishing a chuchu-jelly-filled boot. And the sailor, his other older brother, cackling in delight from the other side of the hall where the Wind is now standing. </p><p> </p><p>“This way is quicker,” he says, and fiddles with the brazier until the fastening <em> clicks </em>and with the slide of smooth stone, a passage is revealed.</p><p> </p><p>“How did you—How did you <em> know </em>that?” Twilight’s eyes are wide.</p><p> </p><p>Time frowns. “I’ve been here before.”</p><p> </p><p>“Really?” the Sky asks. Time doesn’t know why he looks so surprised. The Sky is boundless and endless and forever. Surely he has seen things Time could hardly dream of?</p><p> </p><p>“Is that surprising?” he returns. “It’s not that far.”</p><p> </p><p>The people speak the same language, at least. And the same words are important. Crowns and swords and a queen dressed as a Sheikah. </p><p> </p><p>“No-o,” Wind tells him after a beat. “I guess not, for you.”</p><p> </p><p>“Does this mean we were wrong about the timeline?” one of them hisses. “Is Warriors’ era more ancient than we thought?”</p><p> </p><p>“It can’t be,” Four says back. “Time just must be… well.”</p><p> </p><p>Timelines? Did he hear that correctly? Malon’s been telling him recently that his ears are getting worse. He fingers the ocarina in its pouch on his belt. He hasn’t played the Song of Time in decades. He’s not sure he would remember how it goes if it weren’t for the fact that sometimes he comes into the kitchen and Malon is humming it under her breath, and every so often the scarecrows in the fields will sing it to him instead of the <em> doh-doh-doh-doh-doh </em>he teaches them. Sometimes, when the north wind rolls down into the valley, it drifts in the air like a distant voice. Time—the concept—meanders on with every moment. It follows him around. </p><p> </p><p>“This <em> is </em>a shortcut,” Warriors frowns. “I recognise these walls. This is the back of the council chambers.”</p><p> </p><p>Time doesn’t say <em> I told you so, </em>because that would be rude. But he lifts one corner of his mouth. </p><p> </p><p>They exit the passageway in single file. Warriors’ eyes run over Time twice, solemn, before he throws open the heavyset oak door and steps briskly inside. His boots echo on the polished stone floor.</p><p> </p><p>The conversation inside sputters and dies. The councillors watch the group of gods—and one mortal man—as they approach the end of the table and the familiar woman sitting there.</p><p> </p><p>“You’re back quickly,” the queen observes.</p><p> </p><p>“Your majesty,” Warriors says, and inclines his head. He presses his lips to her gloved hand. Zelda—for she <em> must </em> be a Zelda, a daughter of the Zelda that Time knew ruled this land as a child, perhaps, too young to be the original—smiles. Time stares. She must—she can’t <em> not </em>know that the creature bowing to her is a god. Why does he do it? To blend in? Does he enjoy playacting? </p><p> </p><p>Is this how the War was won? With the patronage of a god?</p><p> </p><p>“I am glad you have returned so promptly,” Zelda tells him. “We were not expecting you back for a number of years. We have much to discuss.”</p><p> </p><p>“Years?” Warriors brow furrows. “How long has it been?” His gaze flicks sideways to Time.</p><p> </p><p>“Seven months,” says the queen simply. “For you?”</p><p> </p><p>“A little over three weeks.”</p><p> </p><p>“Interesting. I assume you were displaced in time?”</p><p> </p><p>“Lost,” Warriors clarifies. “But we were found again.” Again, his face shifts. “Your highness, may I introduce my companions. You are aware of the problems we came across during the war with my—er, namesakes.”</p><p> </p><p>Fellow gods, he means. Is he confuscating the matter for the benefit of the councillors? Can they not taste the power on him?</p><p> </p><p>“I give you Wind, Sky, Hyrule, Twilight, Four, Wild, Legend and Time.”</p><p> </p><p>The queen surveys them with ice-blue eyes. “All of them like you?”</p><p> </p><p>Time feels eyes upon his back. He knows he is the odd man out. He does not mind it. </p><p> </p><p>“Time…” Warriors begins. “He says… He says he was once a Link, but…”</p><p> </p><p>Once a Link. Now a farmer. Now Malon’s husband. Now retired—or should be.</p><p> </p><p>“He believes Hylia wants him on this quest. You must recognise his likeness.”</p><p> </p><p>“I see,” says the queen, slowly. </p><p> </p><p>His likeness? Time frowns to himself. Could his reputation as a hero have spread so far that it somehow reached this distant land? </p><p> </p><p>“Do you require anything… Time?” Zelda asks.</p><p> </p><p>He loosens his tongue hastily from where it has been glued to the roof of his mouth. “Your audience is reward enough for now,” he says, in some awkward semblance of courtly manners. He has never been silver-tongued. That was always the Captain, he remembers. All those years ago. How old would the man be now? Fifty? How old would the Zelda he fought beside be? The one who dressed as Sheik, like an echo of his own princess? “Though it would please me greatly to know your mother is well. She was an admirable warrior in her time.”</p><p> </p><p>There are faint murmurs behind him.</p><p> </p><p>“You are kind,” Zelda observes. The gold on her uniform shines. She wears a filigree circlet rather than a traditional crown. “Strange. I have not heard time to be so.”</p><p> </p><p>She leans forward.</p><p> </p><p>“Then again,” she says, as he wonders what in the sacred realm she is talking about— “I have also heard that time heals all wounds. My mother is long dead.”</p><p> </p><p>Her gaze lingers on the right side of his face. He fights the urge to open his eye. A dull ache sinks deeply into his heart—grief for a woman whose face he cannot remember.</p><p> </p><p>“Maybe the time you are looking for has not yet passed,” he offers, clumsy.</p><p> </p><p>“You are right,” Zelda says graciously. “Please, be seated. I would be interested to see what you make of this.”</p><p> </p><p>The councillors closest to them spring to their feet, stammering about temples. Zelda waves the group forward and servants rush to tuck their chairs in for them, then flee. </p><p> </p><p>“What is going on?” Warriors breathes. He picks up a large document. “The treaty… this should be in the Great Hall. It marks the beginning of a new era of peace. What is it doing here?”</p><p> </p><p>“It is an era of peace that might be shorter than we hoped,” Zelda admits. “Dissent is gathering. There have been skirmishes on the border. We are preparing for another war.”</p><p> </p><p>Warriors makes a face like he’s been punched. “No,” he breathes. “No… the kingdom barely survived the last one. I…”</p><p> </p><p>Does it drain his power, Time wonders, to watch soldiers die? Did he watch Time’s older brother die? Did he cradle his ghost, and tell him that everything would be okay?</p><p> </p><p>He knows with every bone in his body that the captain had been a war hero. If he had survived, he should be in this council chamber, advising Zelda on behalf of her late mother. The sailor belonged to the ocean, and Time will not begrudge an old man his wanderlust—but the captain should have been here, at the queen’s right hand side. </p><p> </p><p>None of the elders in this room have eyes in the right shade of blue. </p><p> </p><p>“I admit, we do not have the finances,” Zelda says. For a moment she sounds so deeply <em> tired </em>that Time wishes to offer her comfort. But what could he say? “The monsters are stirring. They are no longer content to remain in their own territories. There are reports of raids. Trinity Village went up in flames two months ago.”</p><p> </p><p>“Trinity…” Warriors echoes. “But that’s nowhere near the Gate of Souls and the main battlefields. If there is another being collecting power, why is it reaching so far east? Trinity was untouched by the war.”</p><p> </p><p>“I don’t know,” Zelda confides. “All attempts at gathering intel have been unsuccessful. The most we have been able to glean is that the monsters are all passing around news of a humanoid creature. Moderate height, close enough to hylian to be labelled as such at a glance, described as a living shadow. So somebody, at least, is directing them.”</p><p> </p><p>“A living shadow…” Four speaks up. “I’ve encountered something similar before.”</p><p> </p><p>“As have I,” Warriors admits.</p><p> </p><p>“And I,” says Hyrule.</p><p> </p><p>“And I,” says Time. Thick, cloying silence floods the room suddenly. Everyone is looking at him.</p><p> </p><p>“A dark god,” Zelda says slowly. Another thing he doesn’t understand. “Tell us. Will there be another war?”</p><p> </p><p>Time looks around the room. The councillors are staring. The gods are arrayed in an uneven cluster behind him, a mixture of concerned and entertained. Warriors is quiet. Zelda is wide-eyed. There is so much <em> hope </em>in her eyes.</p><p> </p><p>She is slightly older than he ever knew her mother to be, he thinks. The gold glints on her breastplate. But as old as she gets, she will never be prepared for a war. There is no preparation possible.</p><p> </p><p>Why is she asking <em> him? </em></p><p> </p><p>He clears his throat and says the first words that appear on his tongue. “Only when Warriors ceases to care for this kingdom.” The god was her patron, right? </p><p> </p><p>The murmurs pick up again.</p><p> </p><p>“What does that mean?” Zelda demands. “When he ceases to care… when will he? What do you know?”</p><p> </p><p>“Your majesty,” Warriors says, pale-knuckled. “Don’t push him.”</p><p> </p><p>“You can’t be a traitor,” she says fiercely. “You <em> can’t.” </em></p><p> </p><p>Time has said something wrong. He can’t tell what.</p><p> </p><p>“I pledged myself to you, your majesty,” Warriors says. His tone is unnaturally subservient. It makes Time’s gut clench. Something is wrong here. “I have no intention of breaking that pledge. You have to believe—I <em> implore </em>you…”</p><p> </p><p>“I do,” she tells him. “I do. I <em> do.”  </em>But she taps her fingers anxiously against the table as she says the words.</p><p> </p><p>“It would be unwise to stand against divine word,” says one of the councillors. </p><p> </p><p>“What do you propose?” the queen asks, quiet. </p><p> </p><p>Warriors lifts his chin as the room’s focus shifts to him. His face is ashen. What is happening? </p><p> </p><p>“Your majesty, you know how we treat traitors to the crown,” growls one of the advisors.</p><p> </p><p>“That was during <em> wartime,” </em>another one speaks up. “It would be illegal—no, downright inhumane to inflict that in these times—”</p><p> </p><p>“He is only a suspected traitor,” another corrects, side-eyeing Time. “Nothing has been proven.”</p><p> </p><p>“Immortal foreknowledge will be admitted in a court of law!”</p><p> </p><p>“It’s not any worse than what he carried out with his own two hands,” one of them points out. He’s white-haired around the temples and wearing a badge pinned to his robes wrought in the shape of a flower. “More than two hundred of our own former men, dead at his hands. I saw it. He’s always been a risk. Anyone else would’ve snapped.”</p><p> </p><p>Warriors’ mouth is pressed in a thin line. Time tries to imagine him on the battlefields of his childhood. A vengeful god. How had they never met, back then? The Deity barely let Time walk away from any battle, no matter how tired he grew.</p><p> </p><p>“I will accept whatever consequences the state deems fit,” Warriors says.</p><p> </p><p>“Hush,” the queen tells him. Time doesn’t—he doesn’t understand. How can they sit at their table and threaten a <em> god? </em> Command a <em> god? </em>Is he bound in service to the crown in some way? Do gods have to follow the same rules that the fairies and the children do? </p><p> </p><p>Time swallows. Does the council know Warriors’ true name?</p><p> </p><p>Is that why he never saw the god during the war? Did the council keep him separated from the people like a chained dog?</p><p> </p><p>“You can’t do this,” barks Legend from behind. “Look at him. I’ll bet everything he ever did was for you, so you could laze around on that throne debating who lives and dies. More than two hundred dead, you said? Were you the one that gave that order? Is that why you remember it so clearly?”</p><p> </p><p>Muttering breaks out. The councillors begin to bicker.</p><p> </p><p>“I won’t let you scapegoat him because of a <em> possibility,” </em>Legend continues. “You’ve been on the brink of war for months, and he hasn’t been here.”</p><p> </p><p>The words clear a haze from Time’s mind. The councillors think that—? No. No, that’s not what he meant at all—</p><p> </p><p>“Your current problems are no fault of his own,” he says suddenly.</p><p> </p><p>The room settles.</p><p> </p><p>“But they <em> will </em>be?” one of the councillors asks, suspicious.</p><p> </p><p>“I cannot say for certain,” Time says, instead of screaming, <em> why in the name of everything holy are you asking me? </em>He blinks. “The flow of time may take many paths.”</p><p> </p><p>Warriors shoots him a small glance. Gratitude wobbles at the edge of his mouth.</p><p> </p><p>“I still say we should schedule an execution,” someone grumbles. “To be on the safe side.” </p><p> </p><p>Warriors shivers, the movement miniscule and controlled. Can you kill a god with a humble axe? Or would it simply wound? </p><p> </p><p>Unless he is, truly, <em> bound </em>—</p><p> </p><p>“Then he won’t be continuing to care for his kingdom, will he?”</p><p> </p><p>“What, so by your definition the minute he dies, war will erupt? That doesn’t make sense.”</p><p> </p><p>It is possible to kill a god, Time knows. When he closes his eye, he’s still counting—<em> twenty-four, twenty-three, twenty-two. </em>Majora dances on the roof of the tower, wearing the Skull Kid’s wooden body like an ill-fitting costume. You can kill a god, if you try hard enough. If you’re lucky. If you count, very carefully, from four thousand, three hundred, and twenty minutes down to zero.</p><p> </p><p>Hylians melt into poes, when they die. Where do the dead gods go?</p><p> </p><p><em> “Enough,” </em>Queen Zelda snaps. She lifts a gloved hand. “I hear a knock.”</p><p> </p><p>Time flicks his ears. The second time, they all hear it.</p><p> </p><p>“Enter,” Zelda calls.</p><p> </p><p>A thin figure, cloaked in white and indigo, hurries into the room and leans back against the door to close it. She tucks a long piece of blue hair behind her ear. Time’s eyes widen. She is thrumming with magic. The same sort of magic as the ocarina. She smells like the transportation portal he walked through to get to this land.</p><p> </p><p>“Sorceress Lana,” the queen greets.</p><p> </p><p>Not another god, then.</p><p> </p><p>“I saw him,” Lana gasps against the doors. Her eyes pass over the gods, lingering on Warriors, and fix themselves to Time’s face. “I saw the creature we have been searching for.”</p><p> </p><p>Zelda leans forward. “You did? Quick, a description—before he fades from your memory. Scribe!”</p><p> </p><p>Lana has not blinked. “My queen,” she says more slowly, still locking gazes with Time. She smells like the transportation portal. She smells like the ocarina<em> . </em></p><p> </p><p>The ocarina smells like the <em> transportation portal. </em></p><p> </p><p>“I don’t believe there’s any need for scribes and sketches,” Lana says. She lifts a shaky hand and points, index finger lined up with Time’s heart. “The monster was a perfect match for this man.”</p><p> </p><p>“He is no man,” the queen says. What is that supposed to mean? Time doesn’t have the <em> best </em>gasp of hylian gender, but he’s pretty sure he’s not a woman.</p><p> </p><p>Wait.</p><p> </p><p>He stands up. </p><p> </p><p>“Exactly like me?” he clarifies.</p><p> </p><p>“Dead ringer,” Lana says. She looks at Warriors for a moment. “I’ve seen <em> his </em>living shadow before. It wasn’t that.”</p><p> </p><p>“I believe you,” Time tells her. He shifts. His feet itch. He wants to pace. “I know him. I have fought him… a very long time ago.”</p><p> </p><p>He’d been nine. Or sixteen. Or both, or neither—it had stopped mattering so much. <em> You must conquer yourself, </em> Navi had said.</p><p> </p><p>The council exchanges worried glances. The gods murmur among themselves.</p><p> </p><p>He clenches his fists. “I… do not recommend… It would not be wise. To confront him head on. I do not wish to waste your army.”</p><p> </p><p>Could he do it again? Confront the monster face to face? It has been a long time since he fought anything greater than a moblin. </p><p> </p><p>“We will help,” he says. “He will chase me, if I run. He has always chased me.”</p><p> </p><p>What else could a shadow do?</p><p> </p><p>“If he is the cause of your political unrest,” Time continues, “I can’t promise it will fade. But if we travel through a portal, and he follows…”</p><p> </p><p>“That will buy us time,” Zelda finishes. She watches him, quiet. “It’s a good plan.”</p><p> </p><p>It will buy them time. Because they aren’t just transportation portals. They smell of the same magic as the ocarina. This is why the gods are relying on Hylia to create their portals; why Hyrule doesn’t make them himself. Some call her the Goddess of—</p><p> </p><p>They are ruptures in history. They are gaps in <em> time. </em></p><p> </p><p>“So we flee?” Twilight asks.</p><p> </p><p>Time bites his tongue. “We avoid,” he corrects. “For now. Planning ahead saves lives.”</p><p> </p><p>“I don’t like it,” Legend says.</p><p> </p><p>“A dark god,” Wind counters cheerfully. Time’s shadow is no god, but he has other things to worry about.</p><p> </p><p>“That one should stay here,” one of the councillors tries, nodding towards Warriors.</p><p> </p><p>Lana snorts. “What’d he do now? Blow his nose too loudly for you <em> gentleman? </em>”</p><p> </p><p>“We have been gifted divine prophecy naming him—”</p><p> </p><p>“A traitor?” she guesses. The corner of her mouth twists upwards. “Oh, I can’t <em> wait </em>for him to snap. I’m counting on it.”</p><p> </p><p>Warriors’ breath stutters. Zelda mouths, <em> go! </em>Time ushers the group out into the corridor as the council erupts into debate.</p><p> </p><p>“Y’know what?” Legend sighs into the hair stuck to the corner of his mouth. “You can mark this down as my least favourite Hyrule, too.”</p><p> </p>
  </div>
