    <h3 class="landmark heading" id="work">Chapter Text</h3>
    <p> </p><p>“Mine,” hisses Wild, as the portal collapses into itself behind them, a spectacle in its own right, dying in a wave of purple-black sparks. “Mine…”</p><p> </p><p>“Your what?” the god of legends complains. “Your little wilderness? This isn’t a game of mix and match. Time travel just got officially <em> confirmed </em>—” </p><p> </p><p>He shoots a glance at Time. </p><p> </p><p>“We could be anywhere. This might not even be any of ours.”</p><p> </p><p>“It’s in the air,” Wild snaps back at him, and promptly scarpers. They all scramble after him, fetching bags and boots and swords that were tossed aside with the portal. There’s an arched stone wall up ahead, lichen-infected and crumbling, and it stands alone among the trees like a… like an entrance to something. A gateway. A flock of startled ravens the size of big black dogs take flight as they approach. A conspiracy, as Malon likes to call them.</p><p> </p><p>Time travel. <em> Time travel. </em> Time’s head is still reeling. So the other gods come from different eras? Different versions of Hyrule? No wonder they seemed so unfamiliar with his brothers’ Castle and Queen. </p><p> </p><p>He bites his lip. </p><p> </p><p>Was that time travel, too? His brothers’ Hyrule Castle, ruled by a Queen Zelda, fighting a war that he had never been able to find on a map? There’s a sick sort of dread pooling in the bottom of his lungs. Has he been separated from his brothers not by oceans but by <em> time? </em>All these long years? Has the ghost of that unfindable place been inside his own maps all along? Has he been walking on long-forgotten battlefields his whole life? Has he been treading down the graves of men he fought shoulder to shoulder with?</p><p> </p><p>“Time,” Wind complains. “Wild’s being evasive again. Do <em> you </em>know where we are?”</p><p> </p><p>“I’m not being <em> evasive!” </em> Wild yells. “This is <em> mine.” </em></p><p> </p><p>“And how do you <em> know that?” </em></p><p> </p><p>“Settle down,” Time says, like he’s dreaming, like he’s going to wake up into a life where the bones of his brothers haven’t been lost in the dirt under his feet for—it must be centuries. Centuries.</p><p> </p><p>He finds in that single moment he never really believed they could have died.</p><p> </p><p>“Can’t we have just a minute to sit down?” Sky puffs. “Warriors’ guards just chased us down half the citadel.”</p><p> </p><p>They had always been so—so <em> real. </em> In the council chambers he half-expected them to come waltzing in unannounced. In the kitchen at home, rolling out dough, he thinks of them fondly; blond hair in the marketplace turns his head, stops his heart. He knew better than to think he would find them again but still he hoped. As with every piece of his past. He is no good at accepting lost things—maybe, he has always dared to think. Maybe. Malon keeps plates of sugar water on the stiles for his sake. On the windowsills there are candle-stubs in jars, ever-burning. <em> We’re here, I’m here, you’re home.  </em></p><p> </p><p>His brothers will never find him.</p><p> </p><p>“Smell,” Wild says. <em> “Smell.” </em></p><p> </p><p>Time inhales and the wood-sweet smell of the Lost Woods hits him like a boulder to the skull. This new grief slips away out of reach, out of words. It leaves a shadow in its wake. He knows more than feels that his eyes have gone wild. Fairy eyes, Malon calls them, whenever the wind carries an unexpected note of spring, or when the dusk creeps upon him unawares while he’s working. It’s a rush. </p><p> </p><p>The Lost Woods look different. Something in the colour of the trees, the shape of the wind as it curls around them, slow and thick. Leaves rustle like the feathers of a slumbering beast. The grass is longer but thinner, wetter like this new world is suspended in a state of sunshowers and dew. Which god is responsible for this? For this evolution? Throughout all his life, the Lost Woods has never changed, not a breath of new air nor an invasive plant nor a new species of frog. At the wood’s heart, where time holds still, not even the trees grow. Every blade of grass and twig and flower remains exactly where it always was, when he was nine and seven and three. The Lost Woods has never changed in all his life. He thought that meant they never would. </p><p> </p><p>He thought a lot of things.</p><p> </p><p>“It would be wise to—”</p><p> </p><p>“Don’t attempt to tell me what—”</p><p> </p><p>“Well, how many—did <em> you </em>go on, huh? Yeah? That’s what I thought—”</p><p> </p><p>“Don’t get all high and m—”</p><p> </p><p>The gods are arguing. </p><p> </p><p>He takes a step forward. </p><p> </p><p>The easy way leads deeper, to the heart, the places he cannot find again and will lose himself trying. He knows this. He <em> knows. </em>But his heart wishes—there is an ache, deep inside him, an ache that has always been there all his life. And there is only one god that could be responsible for this. One being.</p><p> </p><p>“Uh, Time?”</p><p> </p><p>“He’s… he’s like, wandering away—what’s happening—?”</p><p> </p><p>“Time? Where are you going?”</p><p> </p><p>“I need to see him again,” the words come, almost without him meaning to let them. “I need to. He will have our answers.”</p><p> </p><p>“Do you want Wild to lead you in, then?” the god of Four, whatever that means, speaks up. “He’s done this before.”</p><p> </p><p>“There’s a trick to it,” Wild offers, already fiddling with his curious patterned machine. Metal and glass. It is a strange thing to be so fixed to the hand of the living wilderness. Perhaps it gives the god a tie to the civilised world. Balance within balance. Blue strands of light emerge from the machine to weave together in the air, taking the form of a torch. He taps a few more buttons. “Just need to find some flint—usually these braziers are lit, but—”</p><p> </p><p>“Let me,” his country says quietly, and pulls out a sputtering candle. </p><p> </p><p>“It’s easy once you get the hang of it,” Wild says with a sideways glance at Time. “I mean, we found you in the Lost Woods, so you probably know, but I don’t think your woods had this trick, and mine probably don’t have your way. It gets misty real quick if you step off the path, only the path is—invisible. So—”</p><p> </p><p>“Breathe,” Time says, oddly amused. Wild seems almost like a teenager trying to impress someone. The anachronism makes him wonder. </p><p> </p><p>“What do we have to do?”</p><p><br />“Usually just follow the torches,” Wild says, frustrated. “But the last few times I’ve been here, they keep getting extinguished. And these braziers? They’ve always been lit, even the first time I came. Even when I was twelve. People used to say it was to lure wanderers in. But now that Ganon’s gone, I think I’m—well. Not supposed to be—but.”</p><p> </p><p>“So—”</p><p> </p><p>“The falling sparks from the fire usually show the way,” he continues, holding the torch high and moving in a long, slow circle. The forest laughs. It’s a dark laughter. The sound of fog curling in the shadows of the trees. The sound of rotting meat covered over with fresh-fallen leaves. The sound of the moon on a winter night. Faces loom above them, crooked hands, crooked mouths. “It’s not—”</p><p> </p><p>He turns again, but the sparks fall in every direction, no direction. The coaxing does nothing. The woods remain impenetrable.</p><p> </p><p>Time sighs. </p><p> </p><p>“It’s not working,” Legend says. He looks at Time. Beckoning, waiting.</p><p> </p><p>“These Woods are different,” Time admits. “Not the trees I am used to. But the core of them does not change. I know my way.”</p><p> </p><p>It's blind hope. They seem to buy it.</p><p> </p><p>He steps off the not-path. It is trickery, nothing more. The dewy grass is no safer than the nettles. Both are pretending to be something they are not. He is practised in the art of keeping himself when the forest tries to lure him.</p><p> </p><p>There are eyes on his spine.</p><p> </p><p>As he walks, a soft whistle falls from his lips, but no kids appear at his waist and from behind. The chattering and gurgling and pinching he is hoping for never comes. There are no Skull Kids in this Lost Woods, then. No guardians. Where did they go? All the kids are older than ancient. They would not have given up so easily.</p><p> </p><p>The Lost Woods are closed to them.</p><p><br />“Time?” someone asks. “Why have we stopped?”</p><p> </p><p>“Are you following me?” he asks, bizarrely touched. The gods shrug almost audibly. </p><p> </p><p>“We didn’t have a better plan,” the god of legends says, so vulnerable in his words. So mortal. Magic is a troublemaker; it’s a storyteller’s job to exaggerate, to lie nicely. “You seem like you know what you’re doing.”</p><p> </p><p>Time almost chuckles. If only they knew. If they had been trying to find a token mortal who understood mortal life, he was a terrible stroke of luck for them. Instead he whistles again, sharper, more insistent, a demand rather than a greeting, and the wood responds. Fog leaps up around their feet and washes them into a deep white storm. And there are lights, in the fog, glowing lights, almost-fairies but not quite. A mimicry. A lure. The wind curls around his wrist as if to steal his hand away. It’s made of laughter, he realises. Tinkling, gurgling laughter. Familiar, still, all these years later.</p><p> </p><p><em> We know you, </em>says the fog and the wind. </p><p> </p><p>He does not speak the languages of weather, but he listens. He finds he knows them back.</p><p> </p><p><em> We know you, we know you… </em> the kids whisper. How bored they must have become, to shed their puppet bodies. How lonely. <em> We know you… you returned a long time ago. Now you return again…  </em></p><p> </p><p>“What’s happening?” cry the gods from the depths of the fog. “Where are we?”</p><p> </p><p>“I want to see!” shouts the wind god. There’s a rustling, then a thudding sound and some laughter. “My baton isn’t working!”</p><p> </p><p>“Wind, did you just stomp your foot like a little kid?”</p><p> </p><p>“Shut the <em> fuck </em> up,” the wind complains. “I don’t see you helping get us un-lost, <em> Legend.” </em></p><p> </p><p>“Hush,” says Time. “Nobody is lost.”</p><p> </p><p>“We can’t see,” the sky points out.</p><p> </p><p>“You’d know if you were lost,” Time assures them. “Now.” A silence settles back amongst them. </p><p> </p><p>The kids’ voices float through the air as if riding on motes of dust. Specks of pollen. Sliding along on the back of the heavy fog. Trapped in the fireflies and the glowbugs, false fairy-lights in the fog. Everywhere and nowhere. <em> We see you, we know you… </em></p><p> </p><p>“Now,” Time says again firmly. “No tricks. You know who I want to talk to.”</p><p> </p><p><em> We know you and you know us… </em> sigh the guardians of the Lost Woods. <em> You know there are no outsiders allowed in the heart of the forest.  </em></p><p> </p><p>Time swallows. </p><p> </p><p>
  <em> Not even you, boything… </em>
</p><p> </p><p>The mist thickens impossibly. He is drowning in an emptiness, a colourless void. The air is wet and cold. He takes a step forward and almost stumbles. The gods are shouting.</p><p> </p><p>“Time?” they cry. “Time? Wild? What’s happening?”</p><p> </p><p>A hand creeps into his, small and light, and he squeezes it back before remembering—the kids are gone forever. Gone into fog. Whose hand, then is he holding?</p><p> </p><p>“Time,” says the tiny god of winds, tucked up against his side. “I found him!” He bellows into the white abyss. And then suddenly there’s a line of them, all holding hands, an unbroken string of myths made flesh. He cannot see them but he feels it, he hears it; they are in his bones.</p><p> </p><p>“Hold the line!” one of them roars.</p><p><br />“It’s no use,” Wild says, “we’re not allowed in! The woods are kicking us out! This is what they do—”</p><p> </p><p>“There’s more than one face to every circle,” Time tells the mist. “More than one side to every tree. I will not breach the heart of the woods. You have my word.”</p><p> </p><p><em> The word of a hylian, </em>the kids laugh.</p><p> </p><p>“Who are you talking to?” asks Wind from his side.</p><p> </p><p>“No,” Time says. “Not as a hylian. The children do not lie.” </p><p> </p><p><em> You are not one of the children, </em> the kids say. <em> You never were… </em></p><p> </p><p>“Maybe not,” he says, reluctant to say <em> kokiri </em>aloud, to speak into being the last word of a first language he has forgotten. “But I am what they made me.”</p><p> </p><p>
  <em> Tricky, boything…  </em>
</p><p> </p><p>He allows himself the laugh. “Maybe so. But does my word mean nothing?”</p><p> </p><p>
  <em> We all mean nothing. </em>
</p><p> </p><p>“Enough riddles,” he does not say, because the kids have always loved riddles. “Please,” another word discarded. People have mercy. Forests don’t. “Ask my father,” is what he settles for, though there’s a lump in his throat. The gods are curling around in their ring of handholding to listen to him. </p><p> </p><p><em> The fathertree is soft at the root, </em>says the mist. </p><p> </p><p>“So take me to him,” Time barters. And like an ocean parting, the forest does. </p><p> </p><p>The mist clears for them; the trees lift their creeping boughs and close their toothy maws and shift aside like illusions collapsing. A path appears like an arrow shot from a bow. Time grasps the young hand of the wind god, another illusion, and tugs them all into the woods. The kid laughs as they hurry, delighted, and for a moment the memory of his older brother strikes him through the heart. The sailor used to laugh in the exact same way. Like he was half in awe of being alive. </p><p> </p><p>No longer.</p><p> </p><p>“Who is it?” someone calls, as they wind along the path in single file, hands overlapping. “Who are we going to see?”</p><p> </p><p>“I think I can guess,” laughs the wind. His hand is warm. It’s too much. “A wise old guardian. Heart of the forest.”</p><p> </p><p>Time makes a sound. “He is not the heart,” he says. “Or else we would not be permitted entry.”</p><p> </p><p>“Explain,” Legend says, short.</p><p> </p><p>“He grows around the heart,” Time says, because it is folly to deny a god, and folly to tell one they’re wrong. It’s only a lie in the same way it would be to say that Wind is a child. His father is not called <em>Great </em>without reason, and although the forest has never changed—had never changed—the trees are not without mischief. They might be allowed an audience with one side of his father, but that would not mean they would find the heart. Secret places, hidden places, other sides would remain out of reach. </p><p> </p><p>“The… the Great Deku Tree,” says Warriors, as if remembering something.</p><p> </p><p>“Him?” Wild asks, and Time wonders at his surprise. If anybody would know, if any creature would be worthy, it must surely be the living wilderness. Then it is explained: “your father?</p><p> </p><p>There is a murmuring among the gods.</p><p> </p><p>Warriors hastens closer to Time and Wind. “I used to know a boy,” he starts—then they are spilling through a log-tunnel into a clearing thronged with ferns and thick, luscious flowers. Fine as silk, delicate as lace. The fog has disappeared as if they dreamed it. Sunlight pools in the grass, shines through leaves, turns the world gold. The earth is black and wet and rich. The air smells of rain.</p><p> </p><p>The gods all move to let go of each other. Time almost cautions them otherwise—but they must be far more aware than him of the dangers of the Lost Woods, wouldn’t they? Even here, in this in-between, temptation glows on every leaf. To be lost so deep would be the end of them. Even them.</p><p> </p><p>He watches them breath in and out like tides rising and falling. He hasn’t been this close to his first home since before—since before. They are so much larger than the kokiri he remembers. Like giants, stretching out his memories; almost grotesque in their size, their age. They shouldn’t be here. <em> He </em>shouldn’t be here. He looks the worst of them all. </p><p> </p><p>“Korok Forest,” Wild says, annoyed. “I’ve <em> been </em>here. This isn’t—?”</p><p> </p><p>“Didn’t you say this place <em> was </em>the heart of the Lost Woods?” someone asks.</p><p> </p><p>“I thought it was,” Wild bites back. “You’re telling me, all this time, I wasn’t even—?”</p><p> </p><p>“No,” says Time.</p><p> </p><p>“They told me it was a secret place,” Wild says. “A special place.”</p><p> </p><p>“And it is,” he soothes. What would it look like, the frustration of the wilderness unleashed? Here, so close to this home of homes? Nothing good. Nothing peaceful. “But there is a more secret place, deeper still, where not even gods may visit.”</p><p> </p><p>“Have you been there?” Legend asks keenly.</p><p> </p><p>Time smiles.</p><p> </p><p>“So this is the Great Deku Tree’s—outer side?” Wild struggles. “What are you <em> saying? </em>You can walk all the way around him. There’s nothing hidden here.”</p><p> </p><p>Twilight nudges Legend, mumbling.</p><p> </p><p>Time doesn’t know <em> how </em>it works, only that it does. Shouldn’t the gods be more in touch with a world that slips around? The Lost Woods spin illusions like spidersilk. Here, deep under the shadow of the trees, they spiral. It’s likely that this outer sanctuary is a sliver of his father’s bark, warped into this huge clearing, patched with sun-dappled flowers. He doesn’t know. He doesn’t know.</p><p> </p><p>He knows this, though.</p><p> </p><p>His father has grown. </p><p> </p><p>As Four starts to bicker with Twilight distantly, Time steps forward along the path. Stones are laid out in welcome for them, ringed with puddles as if it has just finished raining. It doesn’t rain here. It never has. There is a triangular stone dias at the end; a notched stone at the centre. A sword.</p><p> </p><p>“I put it back,” Wild says awkwardly. “After.”</p><p> </p><p>After? After what? Is there a hero in this world somewhere, like him? There is an impossible gap in the canopy. Sunlight strikes her. She is glowing. </p><p> </p><p>He looks away.</p><p> </p><p>Away, and past her, and to tree bark. Gnarled and ragged, despite this weatherless place, so old it has become soft as paper, stretching up and up and—it is a root, just a root, not the trunk he was expecting. He presses forward, tugging the wind-child with him, fingers tangled, and the rest of the gods follow, or watch, silent—do gods pray? Do gods dream?</p><p> </p><p>Where the root meets the tree there is a round slice of exposed wood, a cut-away place to stand, and he does. </p><p> </p><p>“Time,” says the wind behind him, and the air gusts a little around them both. Is it rude, to bring gods into his father’s domain? Does he have to introduce them?</p><p> </p><p>It has been so long.</p><p> </p><p>“I never thought I would see you again,” Time starts, truthfully—</p><p>
  <br />
  <br />
</p><p> </p><hr /><p> </p><p>
  <br />
  <br />
</p><p>“Hello, father.” </p><p> </p><p>Eyelashes pressed into his cheeks, forehead smooth, the god touches the tree like a homecoming. From all around the clearing, the creatures Wild described as koroks emerge as if they were called. Like flowers to the sun they turn to him. Their little propellers spin silently. Hyrule gathers the armful of blue star-shaped flowers Wild gives him, watchful. Wary.</p><p> </p><p>“My son,” comes the reply. So it is true. Time’s father is a <em> tree. </em>How does it work? How is a god born of a plant? Did he crawl out of the bushes as a baby, like Wild climbing sopping wet from the Shrine? No. That was a rebirth, from how he tells it. Like Hyrule himself, then, who only remembers the road. Like Time shed his branches one day and stepped out of the soil. </p><p> </p><p>“I never thought I’d see you again,” the god says again. He leans closer. Hyrule sees Wind squeeze his hand a little, for comfort. Warriors’ eyebrows move a little.</p><p> </p><p>The tree laughs. “You could have tried,” it says. </p><p> </p><p>Time shakes his head. “No—I—the kokiri can’t leave the lost woods. We’re—we’re not allowed. I wasn’t supposed to.” He takes a breath, and then another, and then continues, quieter. “I left. I wasn’t swallowed by the lost woods. I—”</p><p> </p><p>“Kokiri,” Wild hisses at Hyrule. “That’s different. I know <em> korok, </em>but—”</p><p> </p><p>“Kokiri,” Hyrule echoes. </p><p> </p><p>“The ultimate test of belonging,” Time admits. “I did not want to be proven wrong.”</p><p> </p><p>“You have not been stolen yet,” the tree says evenly. “Does that not answer your question?”</p><p> </p><p>“I haven’t gone deep enough,” Time responds. He shakes his head. “I haven’t gone deep enough.”</p><p> </p><p>The tree rumbles. Hyrule tenses a little. It’s—he can’t help it. This Great Deku Tree is <em> huge. </em>Beyond the green canopy, there is another higher canopy, a pink one, not made from leaves but great trailing blossoms. Honey-sweet, big enough to contain the entire clearing underneath it. The tree is what Hyrule has been smelling the entire time, he realises. Notes of it in the wind and the fog. Thick enough now at the epicentre that he feels like he’s floating.</p><p> </p><p>Wild darts away. Hyrule grips his flowers and follows, under the mammoth tree-roots, through the grass. There’s a path, a sort of tunnel, more flowers, a few decorated wood-pots. They look a little like huge, hollowed-out nuts, but that would be ridiculous. Tree-nuts don’t grow big enough for Hyrule to put his boots in. </p><p> </p><p>Trees don’t grow big enough to have <em> furniture </em> inside them <em> . </em></p><p> </p><p>“Do you know what he was talking about?” Hyrule prompts, nudging Wild. </p><p> </p><p>Wild scowls. “What does it mean?” he asks the korok on the other side of the cookpot, which is  bubbling away like it was waiting for them. Hyrule eyes the leaf-bed in an alcove curiously. Is that for Wild? Time? All of them? Or is this place like the visitor’s suite of the woods? Time told them all it wasn’t the heart—so what was it?</p><p> </p><p>Wild flicks his tongue, then makes an attempt at curling it into the shape of the word Time had dropped like well-worn velvet. “<em> Kokiri?” </em></p><p> </p><p>The korok burbles. </p><p> </p><p>“Kokiri?” Wild tries again. Hyrule passes him a flower and gives it his own take.</p><p> </p><p>“<em> Kokiri,” </em>he says, with a little bit of fairy in the word. </p><p> </p><p>“Me,” says the korok. </p><p> </p><p>“Not korok, <em> kokiri.” </em></p><p> </p><p>“Me!” says the korok again. Then it laughs. “Ya-ha-ha-ha!”</p><p> </p><p>“If you’re kokiri,” Hyrule says, giving Wild another flower. “Where’s your leaf-clothes? And your hat? And your fairy?”</p><p> </p><p>“You know what a kokiri is,” Wild says bluntly. </p><p> </p><p>“You’re pronouncing it wrong,” Hyrule tells him. “And maybe. I think so. Not by that name, but… little tree-children are in all the legends. They’re a kind of fairy, probably. One died a long time ago, or something that people <em> thought </em>was a fairy, at least. Maybe they made it up.”</p><p> </p><p>The korok squeaks. “We don’t do that,” it says. “Playtime is never over. Fathertree gives us playtime <em> forever. </em> We even get to play in all of Hyrule, now. Now the kids flew away, they can’t stop us anymore! Not strong enough! <em> ” </em></p><p> </p><p>“You really are a child, ” Wild says curiously. “How old are you?”</p><p> </p><p>“Ya-ha-ha-ha!” it laughs again, “ya-ha-ha-ha!”</p><p> </p><p>“The kids flew away?” </p><p> </p><p>“You saw them! They said hello.”</p><p> </p><p>“The,” Wild flexes his wrist. Clutches the pretty blue-white-gold petals in his hand. “The lights in the fog?”</p><p> </p><p>“Come on,” Hyrule says, antsy. “Let’s go.”</p><p> </p><p>“Well, where are your fairies?” Wild spits out, as Hyrule flees from the bowels of Time’s father. Bell-shaped hanging plants light their way. “If you used to—” Hyrule hears a rush of movement, and then Wild is at his side. “Where <em> are </em>the the fairies?” he hisses. “There’s usually some.”</p><p> </p><p>“There you are,” Sky says. </p><p> </p><p>“We’ve got some flowers for you,” Hyrule decides, and shoves Wild and his armful of blossoms off-balance into Sky’s chest. Then he dashes madly away across the grass, snickering to himself. There’s a lightness in the air. A sweetness. He could do a cartwheel right now. With a sudden rush of excitement, he attempts it, and trips over his limbs with spectacular uncoordination. He tumbles over and over, head spinning, laughing harder than he can ever remember laughing, and comes to a rolling halt next to Twilight.</p><p> </p><p>“You having fun there, you little jester?” </p><p> </p><p>“There’s so much <em> magic </em>,” he responds, still laughing, and rolls over in the grass to press his forehead into Twilight’s knee.</p><p> </p><p>“I know,” Twilight says. He’s got his sleeves rolled up and boots off in the grass. He squints down at Hyrule through the sun. “Even I can feel it, and if you’d gave me a magic wand, I’d put someone’s eye out.”</p><p> </p><p>“So’d I,” Hyrule declares. “It’s a pointy stick, what else would you do with it?”</p><p> </p><p>“Magic,” Twilight says.</p><p> </p><p>“Oh…” says Hyrule, as insincerely as he can manage. “Well, that makes sense! Why didn’t <em> I </em>think of that!”</p><p> </p><p>“You little noodle,” replies Twilight, equally fond and exasperated, and lunges over to tickle him. Hyrule has already wiggled out of reach. He can feel dirt on his cheek and he’s going to be <em> so </em> itchy later from rolling around in the grass. He doesn’t care. He’s been feasting on the magic their new resident god trails around for hours now but this isn’t just a feast anymore, it’s a <em> banquet. </em>He shrieks as Twilight almost manages to grab him, legs kicking. Twilight’s a wrestler. If he manages to get hold of Hyrule, he’s doomed.</p><p> </p><p>He’s doing pretty well for himself until he rolls into a tree root, anyway. Twilight gets his evil fingers into the ticklish crease of Hyrule’s hip, and his leather underarmour doesn’t get down past his sternum, so it’s useless. “Ruthless monster!” he accuses. </p><p> </p><p>“I’ll show you a ruthless monster,” Twilight agrees. Hyrule kicks him in the shoulder and scrambles to make his escape, but the root gets in the way. Twilight hip-checks him and rocks back with his ankle and somehow manages to roll them both away from the root and into the sun next to the weird sword pedestal, where he proceeds to sit on Hyrule’s legs and tickle him as ruthlessly as threatened. Hyrule thrashes around and tries to buck him off uselessly. He’s laughing so hard his stomach hurts<em> .  </em></p><p> </p><p>“I’m gonna—I’m—I’m gonna <em> bite you,” </em>he gasps out, still writhing.</p><p> </p><p>“You wouldn’t,” Twilight starts to say with far too much confidence, before Hyrule latches on to his forearm. He yelps like a startled dog and flings Hyrule back across the grass. </p><p> </p><p> “It’s my secret weapon,” Hyrule gasps, laughter fading, and bares his teeth.</p><p> </p><p>Twilight bares his teeth right back. They’re much pointier. </p><p> </p><p>“What do you think of him?” </p><p> </p><p>“The Great Deku Tree?” Twilight asks, thrown by the change in conversation.</p><p> </p><p>“Time, of course.”</p><p> </p><p>Twilight’s eyes flick to the side, and up, to where Wind is dangling his little boots off the side of the root and kicking them around idly. The god himself—both of them, because the Great Deku Tree must be divine or at least immortal, to be this powerful, to have lasted this long—are talking in low voices. Twilight’s jaw tightens, and he starts putting his socks back on. “Kid’s taken a shine to him.”</p><p> </p><p>“What about you?” Hyrule presses.</p><p> </p><p>Twilight flicks his sock out to get the grass off it and doesn’t answer. Hyrule wrinkles his nose.</p><p> </p><p>“If Ordona weren't already keeping an eye on me, I'd pray to him,” he eventually says, gruff. “Between her and the Light Spirits, I'd say my ass is covered.” </p><p> </p><p>“He seems like a good man,” Hyrule returns. He blinks. “Are gods also men? A good deity? Kind, at least. Kinder than I might've thought. I'm sure a lot of people do pray to him.”</p><p> </p><p>“Maybe you should start,” Twilight says, uncharacteristically distant. “Hasn't there ever been nothing you wanted to change?”</p><p> </p><p>“Surely even a god can't fix the past?”</p><p> </p><p>Twilight shrugs. “Time, he said. If not past, then future. O forefather, O counter of heartbeats, O he who keeps the rhythm of stars, grant me peace and long life; let the world not require my sword.”</p><p> </p><p>Hyrule hums. There’s always been a steadiness to the way Twilight talks. A smoothness, a softness. But this is more. The prayer fits in his mouth like it was always meant to be there. Constant and unwavering as the turning of the earth. Constant and unwavering as <em> Time. </em>“Where’d that come from?”</p><p> </p><p>Twilight grunts a little. Shrugs again. He finishes tugging on one boot and starts with the other. </p><p> </p><p>Far above their heads, the sunlight shimmers. Hyrule shades his eyes with a hand and looks up to see a familiar mop of yellow hair. What exactly Wild thinks he’s doing climbing up the Great Deku Tree’s eyebrows, Hyrule isn’t entirely sure, but he’s tempted to join in.</p><p> </p><p>“What does he look like to you?” Twilight says abruptly.</p><p> </p><p>“What?”</p><p> </p><p>“Time.”</p><p> </p><p>“Uh.” How to explain what it feels like? The magic that surrounds the god? The wood-fairy scent? Hyrule can taste the golden goddesses in the air Time leaves behind—and hadn’t that been a trip, to see a god breathing. It reminds him of Legend and his shrouds of magic jewelry, his countless blessings, like every magical creature in the world has staked a personal claim on his safety. “Two legs, two arms, one eye. Gold-plated.”</p><p> </p><p>“He looks like he’s wearing the armour my ancestor died in,” Twilight says, like he’s trying to convince himself it isn’t a big deal. “Just wondering if it were the same for everybody.”</p><p> </p><p>The sound of Wild’s paraglider deploying breaks into the background rustling of leaves. Hyrule cranes his neck up. </p><p> </p><p>“So,” Wild says breathlessly, landing on another root. “I went up to talk to Walton, and the fairies are not happy.”</p><p> </p><p>“What is any of that supposed to mean?” </p><p> </p><p>“Walton’s not—there’s this little pond at the top of Great Deku Tree, in a hollow. Fairies gather there. Every time I’ve been here, there’s been fairies. And now, only a handful, and they are <em> jittery </em>.” He plants both hands on his hips.</p><p> </p><p>“Hm,” says the tree with a rumble, and Hyrule realises again with a jolt how <em> huge </em>he is.</p><p> </p><p>Time takes his palms off the bark and asks, “fairies?”</p><p> </p><p>“They’ve been less frequent visitors, of late,” the tree admits. “They seem to be lying low.”</p><p> </p><p>“Come and see,” Wild challenges.</p><p> </p><p>“Let’s see if I can coax them out,” Time replies instead. Does he just not want to climb his father? Is that too undignified? Should Wild have probably not said that? Is Time the type of god to get offended? “I’ve got something that should help.” Wind hands him his pack and he sticks an arm inside it briefly: emerges with a white oval, painted with huge spiky pink eye-shapes, strung with beads, festooned with great lengths of flowing yarn and ivy. They all blink at it sceptically. Then he fits it over his head and—</p><p> </p><p>“Oh,” Hyrule gasps. “Hello.”</p><p> </p><p>He staggers forward, clutching at a bemused Twilight. It’s like Time is getting bigger, somehow, or maybe the rest of the world is getting smaller. He’s so <em> glittery. </em> And <em> bright. </em>And—</p><p> </p><p>“Whoa, there,” Twilight says, as Hyrule trips over his own feet, but Hyrule doesn’t even have the breath to make fun of him for being a cowboy. He giggles, and lurches forward, closer to Time, closer to the <em> god— </em></p><p> </p><p>Everything is a swirl of sound and colour, but there are fairies, he sees fairies twinkling, zipping in a loop around Time’s head. One passes over him and Twilight on its way to the god and he giggles again; falls to his knees on the grass. Its wings clip the side of his ear as it goes and it’s <em> warm, </em> and it’s <em> bright, </em>and he shivers with the overwhelming splendour of it all.</p><p> </p><p>“Ssh,” Twilight says, hands on his shoulders, forearms, steadying, supporting. “Hush now.”</p><p> </p><p>He sees through a kaleidoscope more fairies, ever more fairies. Several flutter first to Warriors and brush against his hair and scarf before making their way over to Time. The vision swirls, too distinct, too detailed amidst his jumbled mind. Too vibrant, too high contrast. Everything has been turned up too bright. Too bright. Warriors is smiling; the smile swallows universes. Hyrule is drowning in it. It’s so much. It’s so much.</p><p> </p><p>“It’s so much,” he mumbles. Giggles again.</p><p> </p><p>“You’re coming over real funny,” Twilight tells him, concerned. </p><p> </p><p>How to explain to him that sound is fractured? That he sees ten, twenty, fifty copies of every blade of grass and leaf? That there are colours in his eyes that have never existed, and will never exist, and have perhaps always been there just in front of him? Is this what it’s like to be a god? Hyrule digs his fingers into the grass and it is met with a billion individual grains of earth, and ants, and worms, and life—he shudders through the feeling, rapturous, overcome.</p><p> </p><p>“Hm,” says the pink blob that is Time’s face. Only it’s not Time’s face. It’s a woman’s face. A Great Mother’s face. Why does Time have the face of a Great Mother? Where did he get it from?</p><p> </p><p>“S’strange,” Hyrule slurs.</p><p> </p><p>“Steady now,” says Twilight.</p><p> </p><p>“What’s he doing up there?” Sky hisses, coming over to join them, and Hyrule realises that they can’t see Time and his Great Mother face up on the root-platform, they can’t see the invisible colours, they can’t see the beads and the glittering and the brightness. It’s the wrong angle. It’s all the wrong angle. How is <em> he </em>seeing it, even? There’s a root in the way. His eyes are looking around corners. Reality is bent around him, around a straight line between him and the Great Mother. Like gravity.</p><p> </p><p>“There’s a root in the way,” he laughs to himself. “The pink is too powerful for the root. The pink is glowing…”</p><p> </p><p>“He’s gone delirious,” he hears Twilight telling Sky. </p><p> </p><p>“M’not <em> delirious,” </em> Hyrule gasps. “I’m being <em> enlightened. </em>Solids are,” he makes an inarticulate gesture, “persuadable.”</p><p> </p><p>“Delirious,” Twilight says again soothingly.</p><p> </p><p>“You’re blind,” Hyrule says. “You’re all blind<em> . </em> And I can see <em> , </em> I can <em> see </em> . <em> ” </em></p><p> </p><p>The moment the words leave his mouth, the world fractures around him. Every sensation drops out of reach. His vision goes flat and smooth and dull and he’s suddenly filled with an intense conviction that he’s dying and then—</p><p> </p><p>“Holy <em> Time,” </em>says Hyrule. He blinks, cross-eyed. The Great Mother face has vanished. He can’t even see over the curve of the root anymore to Time’s pack, just the soles of Wind’s little boots still dangling off the edge, and the clusters of fairies still hanging around the Great Deku Tree. “What just happened to me?”</p><p> </p><p>“No clue,” Twilight tells him, greatly amused. Hyrule gets up out of the grass. “But it was mighty entertaining.” He clasps a hand to his chest and reclines dramatically across Sky. “<em> You’re all blind! I’m the only one who can see! </em> Hark at the little prophet! <em> ” </em></p><p> </p><p>“That’s not even what I said,” Hyrule grumbles. </p><p> </p><p>He stumbles away from them. Runs up to where the sloped root protrudes from the earth, digs his hands into the bark and half-walks, half-crawls up ungainly. At the top, Wind is humming like it might convince the fairies he <em> isn’t </em>trying to sneak up and bottle them. Time looks solemn.</p><p> </p><p>“What was that?” Hyrule demands. “Where’d you—” he shakes his head, trying to remember what he’d seen. “How’d you get a Great Mother’s face?” </p><p> </p><p>The fairy sitting on Time’s curled index finger takes flight. “I have melodies that could make you know peace,” the god says. “I have items that could drive a man mad.”</p><p> </p><p>Hyrule huffs. “The real Great Mothers don’t make me feel like that.”</p><p> </p><p>“Are the Great Mothers you know healthy?” asks the tree. “Are they prospering?”</p><p> </p><p>Hyrule scowls.</p><p> </p><p>“In any case, the borrowed power of a Great Mother is the least of your problems right now, young one,” says the tree in that all-encompassing rumble. “The fairies have been fleeing a beast.”</p><p> </p><p>“The shadow the council spoke of,” Time says. “He’s here.”</p><p> </p>
